What is Apache Airflow?

Apache Airflow is an open-source workflow orchestration tool used to schedule, automate, monitor, and manage data pipelines.

In simple words:

Airflow helps automate a sequence of tasks that need to run in a specific order.

Without Airflow

Suppose every day you need to:

1. Read data from a CSV/API/Database
2. Clean the data
3. Load it into a Data Warehouse
4. Generate reports
5. Send an email

Someone would have to run these manually.

With Airflow

Airflow automates the entire process.
         Start
           |
           v
    Read Data
           |
           v
    Clean Data
           |
           v
    Load Data
           |
           v
   Generate Report
           |
           v
     Send Email
           |
           v
          End

This complete flow is called a Data Pipeline.


Core Components of Airflow
1. DAG (Directed Acyclic Graph)

A DAG represents the workflow.

Example
      Read Data
           |
           v
      Clean Data
           |
           v
      Load Data
           |
           v
      Send Email
Directed → Tasks have a direction.
Acyclic → No loops allowed.
Graph → Collection of connected tasks.

Think of a DAG as a blueprint of your pipeline.

2. Tasks

Each step in the workflow is called a task.

Task 1 → Read CSV
Task 2 → Clean Data
Task 3 → Load Data
Task 4 → Send Email

3. Scheduler

The Scheduler decides when to run the DAG.

Example:

Every Day at 8 AM
Scheduler
     |
     v
 Executes DAG

